column13:
The abbey of St Victor in Paris (1108) and the approximate position of its daughter abbeys (if known) between the twelfth and thirteenth centuries, occupied by men. For additional female houses and priories see the document entitled ‘List of Victorine Abbeys and Priories’. The name of each abbey is followed by the date of its inclusion to the Victorine federation. Victorine abbeys are as follows:


 France: Dames Blanches de Saint Victor (White Ladies of Saint-Victor), Saint-Servais; Notre-Dame de Cantimpré, Cantimpré (1177); Notre-Dame de Chaage, Meaux (1135); Notre-Dame de Hérivaux, Hérivaux (1175); Notre-Dame de Juilly, Juilly (1184); Notre-Dame de la Roche, Roche (1232); Notre-Dame de Livry (also Livry Abbey), Livry-en-Aulnoy (c. 1186-1200); Notre-Dame du Bourgmoyen, Blois (1122); Notre-Dame du Voeu (Our Lady of the Vow), Cherbourg (1145); Notre-Dame, Boulogne (1360); Notre-Dame, Eu (1148); Notre-Dame, La Victoire, Senlis (1223); Saint-Ambrose, Bourges (before 1170); Saint-Barthélemy, Noyon (before 1140); Saint-Calixte de Cysoing, Cysoing (1198); Saint-Étienne, Soissons (between 1170 and 1228); Saint-Euverte, Orléans (c.1140); Saint-Jean-Baptiste, Le Jard (1224); Saint-Mary, Eaucourt (founded before 1155); Saint-Memmie, Châlons-en-Champagne (1162); Saint-Satur-sous-Sancerre, Bourges (c. 1180); Saint-Nicholas du Pré, Verdun (1226); Saint-Quentin, Beauvais (1160); Saint-Vincent, Senlis (1139); Sainte-Geneviève, Paris (1148);


 England: Keynsham Abbey, Keynsham (c.1172); St. Augustines, Bristol (1148); Worspring (Woodspring), Kewstoke (1210); Wigmore Abbey (St James), Wigmore (1148);  


 Ireland: St Catherine’s, Waterford (before 1207); St Thomas', Dublin (c. 1192);


 Italy: Sant'Andrea, Vercelli, Piedmont (1219);


 Germany: Springiersbach Abbey, Eifel, Germany (c. 1132-1198); Sankt Marien, Ückermünde (1260);


 Denmark: Eskilstrup, Island of Sjaelland (Zealand) (1160); Saint-Thomas du Paraclete, Eskilsø Island /Æbelholt Abbey, Tjæreby (1165); 


 Iceland: Þykkvabær, Iceland (1165);
